                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Ahmedabad, July 31: The Gujarat government has banned mobile phones not only for students on school and college premises but also staff, parents and visitors in perhaps the first move of its kind in the country.           
	Education minister Raman Vohra said, Though we are not against the use of technology but the adverse impact of mobile is very visible. The excessive use of mobile phone among students in schools and colleges is spoiling the education activities. So this nuisance needed to be curbed in the interest of the students.           
	A education department resolution says students up to Class XII will not be allowed to carry mobile phones to school. Also teachers, staff members, parents and visitors will not be allowed to use mobile phones at places in schools where educational activities are carried out. The schools and colleges have been asked to keep land-line facility to enable students and the staff to make calls in urgent situations.                  
	 Kochi (PTI): ) A CBI court on Saturday issued a non-bailable warrant against Claus Trendl, accused in a multi-crore corruption case in which CPM Kerala secretary Pinarayi Vijayan is also an accused.                   
	Chandigarh (PTI): A 22-year-old woman was found dead here on Saturday with multiple stab wounds, police said. Neha, a resident of Sector 38 (West), was found lying beside her scooter near a taxi stand, the police added.                  
	Udhampur (PTI): The army has evacuated about 400 marooned families in Kupwara district, lashed by torrential rain over the past few days. Three choppers were used in the rescue.                   
	Namakkal, TN (PTI): Truckers in the southern states have announced an indefinite strike from Sunday demanding a decrease in highway tolls. While the Centre levies Rs 1.45 per kilometre per lorry, private toll gates charge Rs 3.45. Around 22 lakh trucks are expected to be off roads.                                                                                                                                              
